 Class of 2013
August 27, 2013















Bren School confers 333 degrees in 2012-13 academic year


















UC Irvine commencement ceremonies held in June recognized 27 doctoral, 110 master’s and 196 bachelor’s degree candidates from the Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences. 


Bren School alumnus Roger Andelin (B.S. ’87), president and chief technology officer of Rakuten.com Shopping, delivered the keynote address at the June 15 ceremony for B.S. and M.S. graduates of the Bren School and The Henry Samueli School of Engineering. Sean Thomas Burke (B.S. ’13), who received degrees in both business information management and electrical engineering, served as the student speaker. A campuswide Graduate Hooding Ceremony was held June 8 for Ph.D. candidates.
The following videos and photo slideshow chronicle this year's commencement season activities. 






THE UNDERGRADUATE EXPERIENCEvideo length 2:20 


Bachelor’s degree recipients representing a variety of Bren School majors — including computer science, informatics and business information management — reflect on their UC Irvine experience and share their plans for the future. “I did not know what this major was going to be — if it was the right thing for me,” said Swati Bhonsle ’13, who received a bachelor’s degree in computer science. “But leaving here, I just couldn’t have seen a better four years.”








THE GRADUATE STUDENT EXPERIENCEvideo length 2:47  


Doctoral and master’s degree candidates reminisce about their time as students and researchers at the Bren School. According to Lilly Irani ’13, who earned a Ph.D. in information and computer sciences and is now an assistant professor with the UC San Diego Department of Communication: “I had a lot of freedom here to follow projects that were not only intellectually interesting but also seemed to matter because they affected people in the world.”








KEYNOTE ADDRESSvideo length 11:12


Rakuten.com Shopping president and chief technology officer Roger Andelin ’87 delivered the June 15 commencement address. “You are entering an industry segment that is relevant,” Andelin said in his keynote. “There is so much more to do and to discover with faster computers, more data and better software. I can’t think of a better place to be. Congratulations on a wise choice.” FULL TRANSCRIPT







STUDENT SPEAKERvideo length 7:03 


Sean Thomas Burke ’13, who earned bachelor’s degrees from both the Bren School and Samueli School, spoke at the June 15 ceremony recognizing B.S. and M.S. graduates. “As engineers and computer scientists we must understand our responsibilities,” Burke said in his speech. “We are the leaders with knowledge and ability to help millions. We are the entrepreneurs who must work together to create an impact, and we are the generation that must address future problems.” FULL TRANSCRIPT







HONORS AND AWARDS












Fifty undergraduates from the Bren School received an array of awards, ranging from Latin honors to recognition of outstanding research contributions. Awardees were recognized by Dean Hal Stern at the annual luncheon for graduating students, held June 7 and hosted by the Student Affairs Office. AWARDEES LIST







